However, by the end of the play, Macbeth seems to accept that he cannot control fate. In his nal
soliloquy he describes life as “a poor player”. This metaphor shows how Macbeth thinks of everyone as
actors following fate’s direction. This suggests that he thinks free will does not exist and that his life is
dictated by forces beyond his control.
In the last act, Shakespeare shows how Macbeth’s belief in fate has become a blind belief in his
invincibility. In Act 5, Scene 5, Macbeth discovers that the enemy army is approaching disguised behind
branches from Birnam Wood. This brings a new meaning to the prophecy and suggests that Macbeth’s
defeat is imminent. Despite acknowledging that the Witches have told him “lies like truth”, Macbeth still
maintains in Act 5, Scene 7 that he can’t be killed by “man that’s of a woman born”.
b)Write about how Macbeth’s attitude towards fate is presented throughout the play.
Throughout the play, Macbeth’s actions suggest his uncertainty about fate. Although Macbeth initially
says that “chance may crown me, / Without my stir” after hearing the Witches’ prophecy for the rst time,
he kills Duncan shortly after. This decision shows how his belief in fate uctuates, as he is no longer
passively allowing fate to take its course, but is taking active steps to secure the future he wants.

As Macbeth gains power, he begins to think that he can overcome the fact that Banquo’s descendants
are fated to be kings. By ordering Banquo’s murder, Macbeth says he wants to “champion” fate “to
the utterance”, meaning he will ght against fate making Banquo’s descendants kings. His deant tone
suggests that he believes he is a worthy opponent to combat the fate prophesied for Banquo’s sons, and
will therefore be able to secure his own fate as King by killing Banquo.
While Macbeth seems to have condence in his ability to stop Banquo’s descendants from becoming
kings, his response to Fleance’s escape shows that he is terried of this being fated to happen. When the
murderer tells Macbeth of their failure to kill Fleance, Macbeth says he is “cabined, cribbed, conned”.
The alliterative ‘c’ in these words creates a cumulative effect that emphasises his feelings of being trapped
by his fate, and how there is a part of him that fears he won’t be able to overcome it.
